Czech discovery: a substance that works even in 'stolen' HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds designed to stop the spread of HIV viruses in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not work as strongly on common virus variants as one of the existing medicines.
AIDS is still a disease that cannot be cured.
However, the drug combination can prolong the patient's life and prevent the HIV virus from spreading in the body.
However, taking them is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of viral proliferation has led to the development of resistant viruses against which no medicines are effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, VSCHT (Chemical and Technological University) Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to tackle virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances called metallic carborans have an effect on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
The metallic carbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the virus's propagation in a different way than all the drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new 'improved' compounds, prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
The metal carbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-layered cages made up of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms, coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Domestic and persistent virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus splitting caused by HIV protease, no mature infectious virus particles would be created.
If we shut down the HIV protease, we also shut down the virus's propagation in the patient's body, the scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the CR Academy of Sciences.
In the paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain, which is then systematically altered further.
A little weaker but more reliable
The effects of these substances on HIV protease were tested in the reagent glass, including against their persistent (resistant) variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metallic carborans on the normal enzyme variant is not as strong as that of the medicinal products used in clinical trials, but it does not lose its effect on the resistant variants against which the medicinal products used are often ineffective.
