The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been characterized by wild poses and mutual accusations -- re-emphasized Friday with the release of a document that sets out an ambitious 40 year greenhouse gas reduction, with the most burdens to be borne by the industrialized nations in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases, has both identified the remaining obstacles and shown the way forward.
But it was seen as a major step forward in a negotiation that is running out of time, as over 100 top politicians from around the world will arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, drafted by a UN working group specifically for this purpose, is silent about the amount of money rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can manage global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrial and large emerging countries can limit their carbon emissions and what the upper limit of global temperature rise that policy makers would carry should be.
The process will be given great flexibility, says John Coequyt, chief executive of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to highlight what the UN's leading climate advocate, Yvo de Boer, called "the big picture".
It shows the blueprint for a possible agreement whereby the industrialized nations together would reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, countries could reduce their emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community also gave a boost to the talks on Friday by ensuring that over the next three years it will provide $3.6 billion a year to help poorer countries adapt to the impacts of climate change - from managing floods and droughts to avoiding deforestation.
Friday, however, brought the same verbal fireworks that had shaped last week's conversations.
The US climate commissioner Todd Stern has rejected proposals calling for binding greenhouse gas emissions reductions for industrialized countries compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies if they are not financed by industrialized nations.
This train announced that the Obama administration was taking a harder line with China than Bush administration officials did less than two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without major emerging economies taking action, said Stern, who also complained that the text did not go far enough to ensure that the reductions could be confirmed by outside parties.
Stern made his remarks an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei made a statement saying that the leading American climate negotiator either lacked "reason" or was "highly irresponsible" that he said earlier this week that the United States would not financially help China to cope with global warming.
The future economic direction of the world's major powers is at stake, and there have been breaches both within the industrialized nations and between the industrialized nations and the emerging countries.
The current struggle is about saving individual economies as well as saving the planet, with China and the United States acting on their respective commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take bolder action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that the great powers were fighting over who should bear the cost of curbing greenhouse gas emissions, as even countries affected have moved to take more aggressive steps to hold those countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game that will develop a new economic dominance, says Ulate, who also serves as a regional climate change adviser for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most affected by climate change said they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although leading participants say the talks will lead to a political agreement at best.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, submitted a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said the small island states' offensive "plays political pressure on the entire political process", partly because they are now united and demanding action from emerging countries like China and India.
