The Crib of the Dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The two-meter-long, six-foot-tall animal ran on two powerful hind legs, had a long skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped jaws, and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs to have these body features, report Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in the journal Science Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangäa at the equator.
Tawa is opening a new window into the early evolution of the dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It tells us a lot about the kinship relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began digging at the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We've sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in a day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Triassic, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by the researchers as new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
Find confirms theories about early Dino history
The name "Tawa" comes from the Hopi sun god.
Sterling Nesbitt says it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only found in single fragments".
Other dinosaur experts may not necessarily share the same enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it does confirm some theories about the early history of the dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current theory, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
Many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, however, which is why the attribution of these early dinosaurs is often disputed.
For example, experts debate when the lizards split into their three main lines of development: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor, and the birds, known as "long-legged" four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and the plant-eating ornithicia, which included, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, Nesbitt says.
For example, at the skull of Tawa hallae, researchers found evidence of airbags, which also belong to the descendants of theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the airbags, birds breathe more efficiently than mammals.
In Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related lineage of giant sauropods later also had airbags and lightweight bones, the common ancestor of both groups probably produced this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Because the earliest known dinosaurs lived in South America, the researchers conclude that lizards first appeared there.
Thus, the three lines of development separated early and spread from South America to all the continents, which at the time were still a single landmass as the supercontinent Pangäa.
The fact that the team together with Tawa Hallae found the remains of two other theropods not particularly closely related speaks for itself.
The three cannot be descended from a common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
There are, of course, contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in what is now Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
He thinks that this may be a distorted view, because there are still a number of primitive dinosaur fossils in South America, while hardly any on other continents.
How the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare lineage of reptilian tribe to the dominant land vertebrates of the Middle Ages is still a mystery.
During the Triassic, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and flying acorns, and with numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, the dinosaurs spread throughout the world and developed many new species, while the triassic-Jurassic border kinship died out.
Success story didn't last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs happened to survive, but the other reptiles didn't.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so they could beat the competition out of the field.
At least the success story didn't last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped a group of animals to flourish, which had also developed in the Triassic, and since then has been tempting a shadow existence: mammals.
