75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want children.
This is the result of the study 'Fertility and career of women in Spain', carried out by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 shows that 75% of women in employment see their career opportunities on the labour market as being limited by their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are major differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children depending on whether women work or not and, if so, what kind of profession they do.
Those who do not work outside the home, work part-time or have no fixed employment contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with fixed jobs, especially in the public sector, postpone the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"Women in the age group of 35 to 49 with a fixed job do not have their first child on average until 3.7 years after the marriage, a figure that increases to 4.1 years for women in fixed employment who have taken longer to achieve this and who have not had their first child much later.
In addition, the nature of work has a major impact on motherhood, although less than the calendar in terms of the readiness to conceive", explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor to be taken into account in the age of women at marriage and first child.
According to the survey, the older the person is at the time of marriage and the first child, the higher the level of education.
This difference was also observed in women of the same age.
For example, women in the 35-49 age group, whether they have only a high school diploma or higher education, became mothers for the first time, on average, at 25.1 or 32.1.
Furthermore, there is another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While women with a master's degree get married before their first job and have their first child, women with a high school diploma or a middle school diploma do things differently and first look for a job and then marry and have their first child, Delgado notes.
