Support for braking maneuvers in critical situations is now mandatory
As with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as is now the case with the ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems must become mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly authorised passenger cars and light-duty vans, and a waiting period has been set for the remaining vehicles until the end of February 2011.
The European Union's measures aim to improve the protection of pedestrians, but because of their functioning, these braking systems can also help prevent many accidents.
The emergency braking assistant's task is to apply more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical brake operator, which detects the brake pedal system by the brake force exerted by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure to the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the Bosch vehicle component manufacturer, one third of the drivers involved in an accident did not step on the brake pedal at all before the collision and half of them had not brake off at full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, penetrates the braking system with maximum force, thus reducing the braking time and thus the braking distance travelled by a car during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents - one in four accidents could be prevented with injuries - once the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
The vehicle is then equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and alerts the driver, while also applying a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, the system will help him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant shall apply maximum pressure to the brakes to minimise the damage.
